d: 4 x 200 m \u2192 4 \u00d7 200 m", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_Shtyl"}
{"title_page": "Sam Smith", "text_new": "<!--The subject of this article about a living person uses the gender neutral pronoun 'they', so therefore the article does as well.-->\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{other people}}\n{{short description|English singer and songwriter}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Sam Smith\n| image            = Sam Smith Lollapalooza 2015-9 (cropped).jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Smith performing at the 2015 [[Lollapalooza]]\n| birth_name       = Samuel Frederick Smith\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|5|19}}\n| birth_place      = [[London]], England\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*songwriter}}\n| website          = {{URL|samsmithworld.com}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sam-smith-mn0002509942|title=Sam Smith Biography & History|website=[[AllMusic]]|first=Andy|last=Kellman|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/01/arts/music/05sam-smith-new-album-the-thrill-of-it-all.html|title=The Tear-Stained Confessions of Sam Smith|website=[[The New York Times]]|first=Taffy|last=Brodesser-Akner|date=1 November 2017|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Soul music|soul]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/who-is-sam-smith-a-quick-primer-on-the-u-k-soul-singer-244251/|title=Who Is Sam Smith? A Quick Primer on the U.K. Soul Singer|website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|first=Nick|last=Murray|date=31 March 2014|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/05/29/sam-smith-gay-british-soul-singer/9711681/|title=U.K. soul singer Sam Smith comes out|website=[[USA Today]]|date=29 May 2014|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[pop-soul]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thetylt.com/entertainment/adele-sam-smith-uk-pop-soul|title=Favorite U.K. pop-soul singer: Adele or Sam Smith?|website=The Tylt|first=Deron|last=Dalton|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>}}\n| background       = solo_singer\n| years_active     = 2007\u2013present\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| label            = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]]\n*[[Jimmy Napes]]\n*[[Naughty Boy]]\n}}\n| module         = {{Infobox person\n  |child     = yes\n  |signature =\n }}\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Frederick Smith''' (born 19 May 1992) is an English singer and songwriter. They rose to prominence in October 2012 after being featured on [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure's]] breakthrough single \"[[Latch (song)|Latch]]\", which peaked at number eleven on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Smith was subsequently featured on [[Naughty Boy]]'s \"[[La La La (Naughty Boy song)|La La La]]\", which became a number one single in May 2013. In December 2013, they were nominated for the [[2014 Brit Awards|2014 Brit Critics' Choice Award]] and the [[BBC]]'s [[Sound of...|Sound of 2014]] poll,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25216850|title=Brits announce Critics' Choice 2014 shortlist|publisher=BBC|date=5 December 2013|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01ky6g6/profiles/samsmith|title=Sound of 2014 Profile: Sam Smith|publisher=BBC|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> winning both.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/brit-awards/10511427/Brits-Critics-Choice-Award-2014-Sam-Smith-announced-as-winner.html|title=Brits Critics' Choice Award 2014: Sam Smith announced as winner|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=12 December 2013|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25635440|title=BBC Sound of 2014: Sam Smith |publisher=BBC|date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\nSmith's debut studio album, ''[[In the Lonely Hour]]'', was released in May 2014 on [[Capitol Records UK]].<ref name=\"inthelonelyhour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2013/12/16/sam-smith-announces-debut-album-in-the-lonely-hour-shares-tour-dates/|title=Sam Smith announces debut album ''In the Lonely Hour'', shares tour dates|last=|first=|date=16 December 2013|website=|publisher=Fact|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"[[Lay Me Down (Sam Smith song)|Lay Me Down]]\", was released prior to \"La La La\". The album's second single, \"[[Money on My Mind]]\", became Smith's second number one single in the UK.<ref name=\"moneyonmymind\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/money-on-my-mind-ep/id775088328|title='Money on My Mind' \u2013 EP by Sam Smith|publisher=[[iTunes]] (UK)|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref> The third single, \"[[Stay with Me (Sam Smith song)|Stay with Me]]\", was an international success, reaching number one in the UK and number two on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], while their singles \"[[I'm Not the Only One]]\" and \"[[Like I Can]]\" reached the top ten in the UK. The album won four awards, at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]], including [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]], [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]], [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], and nominations for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]]. \n\nFor Smith's and [[Jimmy Napes]]' song \"[[Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall]]\", the theme for the [[James Bond in film|James Bond]] film ''[[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]]'' (2015), Smith won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Golden Globe Award]] and the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]. Smith's second studio album, ''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'', was released in November 2017 and debuted atop the UK and US album charts. The lead single, \"[[Too Good at Goodbyes]]\", reached number one in the UK and Australia and number four in the US. Smith released the single \"[[Promises (Calvin Harris and Sam Smith song)|Promises]]\" with [[Calvin Harris]], and it reached number one in the UK. Smith initially released \"[[Dancing with a Stranger]]\", with [[Normani]], as the lead single for Smith's [[Upcoming Sam Smith album|third studio album]], which reached the top ten in the UK and the US and was nominated for [[Brit Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] at the [[2020 Brit Awards]], along with \"[[How Do You Sleep? (Sam Smith song)|How Do You Sleep?]]\", a cover of [[Donna Summer|Donna Summer's]] 1977 classic \"[[I Feel Love (Sam Smith song)|I Feel Love]]\", and \"[[To Die For (Sam Smith song)|To Die For]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/sam-smith-announces-new-album-to-die-for/|title=Sam Smith Announces New Album To Die For, Shares New Song|last=Bloom|first=Madison|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> until the album was postponed due to the 2020 [[Coronavirus disease|Covid-19]] pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/sam-smith-explains-why-they-changed-to-die-for-album-title-and-its-release-date-amid-coronavirus|title=Sam Smith explains why they changed to die for album title|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The single \u201c[[I'm Ready (Sam Smith and Demi Lovato song)|I'm Ready]]\u201d with [[Demi Lovato]], was then released as the lead single for the upcoming album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9360112/sam-smith-demi-lovato-im-ready-video|title=Sam Smith & Demi Lovato&#39;s &#39;I&#39;m Ready&#39; Video: Watch|date=2020-04-16|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nSmith has won four [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]], three [[Brit Awards]], three [[Billboard Music Award|Billboard Music Awards]], and an [[American Music Awards|American Music Award]], as well as a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe]] and an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] through their career. Smith is [[genderqueer]] and uses [[singular they]] pronouns.<ref name=\"pronouns\" /><ref name=\"pronouns 2\" />\n\n==Early life==\nSamuel Frederick Smith<ref>{{cite web |url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/writer.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&querytype=WriterID&keyid=1481472&keyname=SMITH+SAMUEL+FREDERICK&CAE=686735199&Affiliation=PRS |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140131205650/http://repertoire.bmi.com/writer.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&querytype=WriterID&keyid=1481472&keyname=SMITH+SAMUEL+FREDERICK&CAE=686735199&Affiliation=PRS |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 January 2014 |title=Songwriter/Composer: Smith, Samuel Frederick |work=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] |accessdate=17 May 2014 }}</ref> was born on 19 May 1992<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sam-smith-mn0002509942/biography | title= Artist Biography |first= James | last= Wilkinson | publisher=AllMusic.com | accessdate= 28 May 2014}}</ref> in [[London]] to Frederick Smith and broker Kate Cassidy.<ref name=allmusic /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/4445012/Banker-claims-she-was-sacked-for-promoting-sons-pop-career.html|title=Banker claims she was sacked for promoting son's pop career|author=Daily Telegraph reporter|date=3 February 2009|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> Smith was bullied for [[gynecomastia]] as a child and had liposuction at age 12.<ref name=\"Wong\">{{cite news |last1=Wong |first1=Curtis M. |title=Sam Smith Opens Up About Gender Identity, Body Image In Candid Interview |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/sam-smith-gender-identity-interview_n_5c8bf783e4b0d7f6b0f34199 |accessdate=March 17, 2019 |work=HuffPost |date=March 15, 2019}}</ref> They were part of [[British Youth Music Theatre|Youth Music Theatre UK]] and appeared in the troupe's 2007 production of ''Oh! Carol'', a musical featuring the music of [[Neil Sedaka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youthmusictheatreuk.org/alumni|title=Alumni Youth Music Theatre UK|date=17 December 2013}}</ref> Before entering the musical theatre, Smith had been in jazz bands.<ref name=\"bestfit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thelineofbestfit.com/features/interviews/sam-smith-every-day-i-think-about-how-insane-this-is-145738|title=Sam Smith: \"Every day I think about how insane this is\"|work=The Line Of Best Fit|date=14 February 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> While studying studied singing and songwriting under jazz pianist [[Joanna Eden]] for a number of years,<ref name=\"fader\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/05/28/sam-smith-cover-story-interview/|title= Sam Smith Opens up About Life and Love|work=[[The Fader]]|accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref> Smith attended [[St Mary's Catholic School (Bishop's Stortford)|St Mary's Catholic School]] in [[Bishop's Stortford]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/News/Bishops-Stortford/Former-Stortford-schoolboy-Sam-Smith-gears-up-for-tonights-Brit-Awards-20140219164127.htm|title=Former Stortford schoolboy Sam Smith gears up for tonight's Brit awards|date=19 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531131254/http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/News/Bishops-Stortford/Former-Stortford-schoolboy-Sam-Smith-gears-up-for-tonights-Brit-Awards-20140219164127.htm|archivedate=31 May 2014}}</ref> and was a member of the Bishop's Stortford Junior Operatics (now Bishops Stortford Musical Theatre Society) and the Cantate Youth Choir.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cantate.co.uk|title=Home \u2013 cantate.co.uk|publisher=Cantate.co.uk|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n===2008\u20132009: Career beginnings with debut singles===\nSmith released two singles before 2010, \"Bad Day All Week\" and \"When It's Alright\".\n\n===2012\u20132013: Breakthrough===\nSmith was featured on the [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]] song \"[[Latch (song)|Latch]]\", which was released on 8 October 2012 and peaked at No. 11 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. In February 2013, Smith released the first single from the debut album, \"[[Lay Me Down (Sam Smith song)|Lay Me Down]]\", and later in the year featured on [[Naughty Boy]]'s single \"[[La La La (Naughty Boy song)|La La La]]\". It was released on 19 May 2013 and peaked at No. 1 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Smith's first EP ''[[Nirvana (EP)|Nirvana]]'' was released the following year. The first song on the EP, titled \"[[Safe with Me]]\", is produced by Two Inch Punch and was first broadcast on [[MistaJam]]'s [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] show on 24 July 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crackintheroad.com/music/23303-new-sam-smith-safe-with-me/|title=New: Sam Smith \u2013 Safe With Me|publisher=Crack in the Road|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=24 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006123254/http://www.crackintheroad.com/music/23303-new-sam-smith-safe-with-me#|archive-date=6 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The second song on the EP is titled \"Nirvana\" and is produced by Craze & Hoax and Jonathan Creek. The EP also includes Smith's acoustic solo version of \"Latch\" and a live version of \"I've Told You Now\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/nirvana-ep/id708375165|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Nirvana \u2013 EP by Sam Smith|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> Smith released the Disclosure, [[Nile Rodgers]], and [[Jimmy Napes]] collaboration \"Together\" on 25 November 2013 as the only single from ''[[Settle: The Remixes]]''.\n\n===2014\u20132016: ''In the Lonely Hour'' and international success===\n[[File:Sam Smith 2 (15425586230).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Smith singing in Glasgow in 2014]]\nThe second single from Smith's debut album, titled \"[[Money on My Mind]]\", was released on 16 February 2014. It was announced on 16 December that Smith's debut studio album, titled ''[[In the Lonely Hour]]'', would be released on 26 May 2014 through [[Capitol Records]].<ref name=\"inthelonelyhour\"/> Smith described the album as \"all about unrequited love\" as a result of personal experience, having never been loved back by any of their love interests.<ref name=\"Sound of Boston\">{{cite web|url=http://soundofboston.com/angel-cambridge-sam-smith/|title=The Angel of Cambridge: Sam Smith|work=Sound of Boston|last=Ollman|first=Jonah|date=28 March 2014|accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref> The album reached number one in the [[UK Albums Chart]] and number two on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and by 5 November it had become the second biggest selling album of 2014 in the US behind only ''[[1989 (Taylor Swift album)|1989]]'' by [[Taylor Swift]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|title=Official: Taylor Swift's '1989' Debuts With 1.287 Million Sold In First Week|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6304536/official-taylor-swifts-1989-debuts-with-1287-million-sold-in|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=4 November 2014|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sam-smiths-debut-album-on-track-to-knock-coldplay-off-number-1-3042/|title=Sam Smith's debut album on track to knock Coldplay off Number 1|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref> In January 2015, ''In the Lonely Hour'' was named the second best selling album of 2014 in the UK, behind ''[[x (Ed Sheeran album)|x]]'' by [[Ed Sheeran]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30641372 \"UK album chart for 2014 dominated by British artists\"]. BBC. Retrieved 1 January 2014.</ref> A live version of album track \"I've Told You Now\", performed at [[St Pancras Old Church]], was made available as a free download as part of an [[Amazon.com]] promotion on 27 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Told-Live-Pancras-Church-London/dp/B00HG1ANVM|title=I've Told You Now (Live at St Pancras Old Church, London): Sam Smith|date=27 December 2013|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402175656/http://www.amazon.co.uk/Told-Live-Pancras-Church-London/dp/B00HG1ANVM#|archive-date=2 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album track \"Make It To Me\", co-written by Howard of Disclosure and Jimmy Napes, was made available as a free download as part of an [[iTunes Store]] promotion on 13 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/make-it-to-me-single/id785860884|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Make It To Me \u2013 Single by Sam Smith|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=13 January 2014}}</ref> Smith went on their debut American headlining tour in the second quarter of 2014, with a setlist of primarily new material.<ref name=\"Sound of Boston\"/>\n\nOn 20 January 2014, Smith made their American television debut performing \"Latch\" with Disclosure on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]''. Smith also performed on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on 29 March 2014, performing the [[Gospel music|gospel]]-tinged \"[[Stay with Me (Sam Smith song)|Stay with Me]]\" and an acoustic version of \"Lay Me Down\".<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1724912/meet-sam-smith-british-bartender-set-take-saturday-night-live-stage.jhtml|title=Meet Sam Smith: The British Bartender Set To Take The 'Saturday Night Live' Stage - MTV.com|work=[[MTV]]|last=Montgomery|first=James|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"vh1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2014-03-28/sam-smith-saturday-night-live|title=Get To Know Sam Smith Before He Plays Saturday Night Live \u2013 Music News + Gossip \u2013 VH1 Music|work=[[VH1]]|last=Exton|first=Emily|date=28 March 2014|accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"queerty\">{{cite web|url=http://www.queerty.com/is-sam-smith-the-worlds-next-great-male-diva-20140327|title=Is Sam Smith The World's Next Great Male Diva? / Queerty|work=[[Queerty]]|last=Tharrett|first=Matthew|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref> \"Stay with Me\" reached number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number two on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>[http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2014-05-31/ \"2014 Top 40 Official Singles Chart UK Archive (31 May 2014)\"]. Official Charts Company. Retrieved 5 December 2014.</ref><ref name=\"Billboard\">[http://www.billboard.com/artist/5811918/Sam+Smith/chart?f=379 \"Sam Smith Album & Single Chart History\"]. Billboard. Retrieved 5 December 2014.</ref> The fourth single from the album, \"[[I'm Not the Only One]]\", reached number three in the UK and number five in the US.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\nIn June 2014, Smith first appeared on the cover of ''[[The Fader]]'' in its 92nd issue.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/05/28/sam-smith-cover-story-interview/ | title=Cover Story: Sam Smith Opens Up About Life and Love | publisher=The FADER | work=The FADER | date=28 May 2014| accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> In August 2014, their single \"Stay with Me\" was named Variance Magazine's Song of Summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://variancemagazine.com/sounds/3312-songs-of-summer-2014 |title=Readers Select 2014 Songs of Summer |publisher=Variancemagazine.com |date=12 August 2014 |accessdate=22 August 2014}}</ref> Smith performed \"Stay With Me\" live at the [[2014 MTV Video Music Awards]] on 24 August at [[The Forum (Inglewood)|The Forum]] in [[Inglewood, California]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sam Smith Is Performing at the 2014 VMAs And Tears Are Unavoidable|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1902436/sam-smith-vma-perfomer/?utm=share_twitter|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> On 15 November 2014, they joined the charity group [[Band Aid 30]] along with other British and Irish pop acts, recording the latest version of the track \"[[Do They Know It's Christmas?]]\" at [[Sarm West Studios]] in [[Notting Hill]], London, to raise money for the [[2014 Ebola outbreaks|2014 Ebola crisis]] in [[Western Africa]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Band Aid 30: One Direction among celebrity line-up|newspaper=Telegraph|date=11 November 2014 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11220735/Band-Aid-30-line-up-revealed.html |accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Sam_Smith_Lollapalooza_2015-3.jpg|thumb|right|upright|250px|Smith performing \"Stay With Me\" in Berlin, Germany in 2015]]\nIn 2015, it came to light that singer [[Tom Petty]], noting similarities between \"Stay with Me\" and his 1989 hit song \"[[I Won't Back Down]]\", had negotiated an out-of-court settlement with Smith in October 2014. Petty and co-composer [[Jeff Lynne]] were awarded 12.5 percent of the royalties from \"Stay with Me\", and the names of Petty and Lynne joined James John Napier (known professionally as [[Jimmy Napes]]) in the [[ASCAP]] song credit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/01/tom-petty-awarded-songwriting-royalties-for-sam-smiths-stay-with-me/|title=Update: Tom Petty awarded songwriting royalties for Sam Smith's \"Stay With Me\" \u2013 Consequence of Sound|work=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]], held on 8 February 2015, at the [[Staples Center]] in Los Angeles, Smith performed \"Stay with Me\" and also received four Grammy Awards: [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]], [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] (for \"Stay with Me\") and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]] (for ''In the Lonely Hour'').<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-31164562 \"Grammy Awards: Sam Smith wins four prizes\"]. BBC. Retrieved 26 February 2015.</ref> At the [[2015 Brit Awards]] held at [[The O2 Arena]] in London on 25 February, they performed \"Lay Me Down\", and won the Brit Awards for [[British Breakthrough Act]], and Global Success.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30839967 \"Brit Awards 2015: Winners list\"]. BBC. Retrieved 26 February 2015.</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, \"Lay Me Down\" was re-released as the sixth single from the album, peaking at number 8 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 (Smith's third US top 10 single).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6502503/mark-ronson-bruno-mars-hot-100-sam-smith-fetty-wap|work=Billboard|title=Mark Ronson, Bruno Mars Lead Hot 100; Sam Smith, Fetty Wap Hit Top 10|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=18 March 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> The same month, Smith recorded another version of the song, featuring [[John Legend]], for the British charity telethon [[Comic Relief]], which reached number one in the UK.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/31902835 \"Sam Smith scores double number one in the UK charts\"]. BBC. Retrieved 20 March 2015</ref>  At the [[2015 Billboard Music Awards]] on 17 May, Smith received three Billboard Awards: Top Male Artist, Top New Artist, and Top Radio Songs Artist.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/6568580/billboard-music-awards-2015-winners-list|title=Billboard Music Awards 2015: See the Full Winners List|date=17 May 2015|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref> They featured on [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]]'s single \"[[Omen (Disclosure song)|Omen]]\", which was released on 27 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2015/07/disclosure-new-song-and-video-omen-f-sam-smith|title=Disclosure and Sam Smith Connect On \"Omen\"|date=27 July 2015|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2015, Smith and Jimmy Napes confirmed that they had composed \"[[Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall]]\", the theme song to ''[[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]]'', the 24th [[James Bond in film|James Bond]] film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34176304|title=Sam Smith records Bond's Spectre theme tune|author=BBC News reporter|date=8 September 2015|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref> The song was released on 25 September 2015 and became the first James Bond theme to reach number one in the UK.<ref name=\"Bond\"/> On 19 October, Smith was presented with two ''[[Guinness World Records]]''\u2014one for recording the first [[James Bond music|James Bond theme song]] to go to number one in the UK and another for scoring the most consecutive weeks in the UK top 10 by a debut album, for ''In the Lonely Hour''.<ref name=\"Bond\">{{cite news|title=Sam Smith's Stay With Me named song of the year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34571560|agency=BBC|date=20 October 2015}}</ref> At the [[73rd Golden Globe Awards]] on 10 January 2016, they received the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Award for Best Original Song]] for \"Writing's on the Wall\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Golden Globes 2016: The Revenant wins top three awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35267777|publisher=BBC|date=11 January 2015}}</ref> On 14 January, the song earned Smith an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/oscar-nominations-complete-list-855398 |title=Oscar Nominations: The Complete List |work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> In the nominations for the [[2016 Brit Awards]] announced on 14 January, the song was among the nominees for Best British Video.<ref>{{cite news|title= Brit Awards 2016: The nominations |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35319213 |work= BBC News Online |date= 14 January 2016 |accessdate= 22 January 2016}}</ref> Smith performed \"Writing's on the Wall\" at the Academy Awards on 28 February and, along with Napes, collected the prize for Best Original Song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sam-smith-wins-oscar-for-his-james-bond-spectre-theme-song-writings-on-the-wall__13954/|title=Sam Smith wins Oscar for his James Bond Spectre theme song|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=29 February 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref> In their acceptance speech, Smith referenced an article by [[Ian McKellen]] published before the awards ceremony that claimed no openly gay man had won an Oscar for Best Actor; Smith misquoted McKellen as saying that no gay man in general had won an Oscar. This was quickly discredited by openly gay recipient [[Dustin Lance Black]],<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.musictimes.com/articles/66393/20160229/sam-smith-mistakenly-thought-first-openly-gay-man-win-oscar.htm| title = Sam Smith Gaffes at Oscars with Misinformed Acceptance Speech, Shaky Performance| date = 29 February 2016| website = Music Times| accessdate = 1 March 2016}}</ref> but McKellen mentioned that the error \"doesn't detract\" from Smith's achievement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/01/arts/sam-smith-the-only-openly-gay-oscar-winner-not-really.html |title=Sam Smith, the Only Openly Gay Oscar Winner? Not Really |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Yonette |last=Joseph |date=29 February 2016 |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''The Thrill of It All''===\nThroughout 2016, Smith released footage of themself in the studio working on new music, leading up to the release of their second studio album. In late 2016, Smith was said to be working with [[Adam Lambert]] on new material. In early 2017, it was reported that Smith would be releasing their second album in September 2017 and had recorded with constant collaborator [[Jimmy Napes]] and [[Naughty Boy]]. In April 2017, Smith was said to have been in studio sessions with [[classical crossover]] group [[Clean Bandit]], working on a possible \"comeback single\". Along with Clean Bandit, record producer [[Timbaland]] and musician [[Frances (musician)|Frances]] said they had worked on songs for Smith's next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/music/clean-bandit-working-on-comeback-song-with-sam-smith/article_248112b6-c023-5ba5-8f78-8cd829bb6a39.html|title=Clean Bandit working on comeback song with Sam Smith?|publisher=NWI Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2017, Smith released a new single titled \"[[Too Good at Goodbyes]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://360musicng.org/sam-smith-good-goodbyes-official-single-cover/|title=Sam Smith \u2013 Too Good At Goodbyes (Official Single Cover)|work=360musicng.org|date=4 September 2017}}</ref> which debuted at number one in the United Kingdom and number five on the US Billboard Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Jack|title=Sam Smith scoops his sixth UK Number 1 single with Too Good at Goodbyes|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sam-smith-scoops-his-sixth-uk-number-1-single-with-too-good-at-goodbyes__20436/|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=15 September 2017|date=15 September 2017}}</ref> Their second studio album, ''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'', debuted atop the UK Albums Chart and the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming their first number one album in the US.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8038264/sam-smith-billboard-artist-100-the-thrill-of-it-all|title=Sam Smith Hits No. 1 on Billboard Artist 100, Thanks to 'The Thrill of It All' Debut|work=Billboard|access-date=15 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sam-smith-s-the-thrill-of-it-all-debuts-at-number-1-on-the-official-albums-chart-this-is-a-dream-come-true-__20979|title=Sam Smith's The Thrill Of It All debuts at Number 1 on the Official Albums Chart: \"This is a dream come true\"|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|author=Rob Copsey|date=10 November 2017|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref> On 20 March 2018, Smith started The Thrill of It All Tour, which visited Europe, North America, Asia, New Zealand and Australia. On 27 March 2018, they released \"[[Pray (Sam Smith song)|Pray]]\" featuring American rapper [[Logic (musician)|Logic]]. On 17 August 2018, the singer collaborated as the main vocalist on [[Calvin Harris]]'s new track \"[[Promises (Calvin Harris and Sam Smith song)|Promises]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenocturnaltimes.com/calvin-harris-sam-smith-debut-promises/|title=Calvin Harris & Sam Smith Debut \"Promises\" {{!}} The Nocturnal Times|website=www.thenocturnaltimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2 December 2018}}</ref> The song became Smith's seventh number one hit on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and their first top song on ''Billboard'''s [[Dance/Mix Show Airplay]] chart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8478334/calvin-harris-ties-rihanna-dance-mix-show-airplay-chart-toppers|title=Calvin Harris Ties Rihanna for Most Dance/Mix Show Airplay Chart No. 1s With 'Promises'|work=Billboard|access-date=2 December 2018}}</ref> They also released the song \"[[Fire on Fire]]\" as the ''[[Watership Down (miniseries)|Watership Down]]'' soundtrack.\n\n===2019\u20132020: Third album===\nIn January 2019, Smith released the song \"[[Dancing with a Stranger]]\" with [[Normani]] as a single and it reached the top ten in the UK, the US and other countries.\n\nOn 6 July 2019, [[New 102.7]] radio host Mike Adam announced the song \"[[How Do You Sleep? (Sam Smith song)|How Do You Sleep?]]\" on their Twitter account on 6 July.<ref name=\"Mike Adam\">{{cite tweet|user=MikeAdamOnAir|number=1147316780173529089|title=New music from @samsmith is on the way!!! Sam will drop \"HOW DO YOU SLEEP?\" on July 19th!!! The upcoming #SamSmith single was written with Savan, IIya and Max Martin... if that isn't a recipe for a great song, I don't know what is!|date=6 July 2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> On 9 July 2019, Smith posted on social media that an announcement would be made the following day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=samsmith|number=1148592325398007809|title=\ud83d\udd25\ud83e\udde1 sound on \ud83d\udc9b\ud83d\udd25|date=9 July 2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://portalpopline.com.br/sam-smith-prepara-anuncio-especial-para-esta-quarta-feira-10/|title=Sam Smith prepara an\u00fancio especial para esta quarta-feira (10)|website=Portalpopline|language=Portuguese|last=Medeiros|first=Kavad|date=9 July 2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> The pre-order link became active on 10 July,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://samsmith.world/HDYS|title=Sam Smith \u2013 How Do You Sleep?|website=samsmith.world|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> and later the same day, they formally announced and shared a clip of the song.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=samsmith|number=1148921364377735169|title=HOW DO YOU SLEEP? July 19th|date=10 July 2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, in a new interview with ''The Zach Sang Show'', Smith expressed excitement about their upcoming record, which will land sometime in 2020. The singer also confirmed that their newest offering will feature fewer ballads and plenty of poppier tracks in the vein of their recent two previous singles. \"I feel like I have recently shown a side of me which I normally keep to myself or for my family and friends,\" Smith told Sang. \"I showed everyone it and everyone loved it. It's almost given me permission to kinda do what I've always dreamed of doing but I was always scared to do, which is pop music.\" The singer also described having been spurred on to write new music following a 2018 collaboration with Calvin Harris, \"Promises\". \"I just naturally started getting back into the studio and started to write,\" they said. \"I caught this wind and started riding this wave and I haven't stopped writing since.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/sam-smith-confirms-new-album-coming-2020-2555740|title=Sam Smith confirms new pop-driven album is coming in 2020|date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February 2020, Smith revealed that a third studio album, then titled ''To Die For'', was scheduled to be released on 1 May 2020.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[MTV]]|author=Trey Alston|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 13, 2020|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3156531/sam-smith-to-die-for-album-announcement/|title=SAM SMITH TEASES NEW ALBUM WITH A (LITERALLY) GRABBY PHOTO}}</ref> Later on in the promotion, the album's release date was pushed back to June 2020.\n\nOn 30 March 2020, Smith announced that, due to the ongoing effects of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], they would be delaying the release of their [[Upcoming Sam Smith album|third album]] and would include a number of changes to the album track list and the title, as they would continue to work on it. However, they did state that it would still be released sometime within 2020.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B-XD8Vag2Kp/</ref>\n\n==Influences==\n{{multiple image\n| footer    = Smith cites [[Adele]] (left) and [[Amy Winehouse]] (right) as primary influences\n| image1    = ADELE LIVE 2016 - HELLO - ST.PAUL - night 1 - Copy.jpg\n| alt1      =Adele\n|width1  = 120\n| image2    = Amy Winehouse f4962007 crop.jpg\n| alt2      =Amy Winehouse\n|width2     = 120\n|align=right\n}}\nSmith cites [[Adele]] and [[Amy Winehouse]] as primary influences.<ref name=\"Capital FM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/sam-smith/news/adele-inspiration/|title=\"I Look Up To Her\" \u2013 Sam Smith On Being Inspired By Adele|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"4music\">\"This Week's Fresh Music\" (17 May 2014). [[4Music]]. Retrieved 28 July 2015</ref> In an interview with ''Rolling Stone'', they cited [[Whitney Houston]] and [[Mariah Carey]] as the greatest R&B voices.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Sam Smith Breaks Down 10 Great R&B Voices|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sam-smith-breaks-down-10-great-r-b-voices-20140513|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sam Smith: 5 Fact Facts About The 2015 Grammy Winner|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/sam-smith-5-fact-facts-about-2015-grammy-winner-1809396|website=International Business Times|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref> The singer also lists [[Chaka Khan]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]], and [[Lady Gaga]] as influences. Asked about the \"diva qualities\" of Smith's voice, the singer remarked:\n{{quote|\"It's all I listened to. I actually didn't listen to male vocalists until about two years ago. I just listened to Whitney Houston, [[Chaka Khan]]. Massive voices.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC Sound of 2014: Sam Smith|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-25635440|work=BBC News}}</ref>}}\n\nIn an October 2017 interview for ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'' magazine, Smith spoke of the impact of the success of Smith's close friend [[Ed Sheeran]]. \"It makes you push yourself. Watching him this past year has just been incredible, but yeah, of course it makes me hungry.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Sam Smith: Watching Ed Sheeran makes me push myself|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/news/sam-smith-watching-ed-sheeran-makes-me-push-myself-36130631.html|date=10 December 2017|website=Belfast Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn May 2014, Smith came out to the public as [[gay]], and acknowledged a relationship\u2014since ended\u2014with actor and model Jonathan Zeizel.<ref name=\"eonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/546310/sam-smith-opens-up-about-being-gay-reveals-album-is-about-a-guy-who-didn-t-love-him-back|title=Sam Smith Opens Up About Being Gay, Reveals Album Is About a Guy Who Didn't Love Him Back|last=Malec|first=Brett|date=29 May 2014|publisher=E!|accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/30931139|title=Sam Smith confirms break-up on stage in Toronto|publisher=BBC|date=22 January 2015|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] when \"Stay with Me\" won an award for Record of the Year, they said, \"I want to thank the man who this record is about, who I fell in love with last year. Thank you so much for breaking my heart because you got me four Grammys!\"<ref>[http://www.popsugar.com/entertainment/Sam-Smith-Grammys-Acceptance-Speeches-2015-36819757#photo-36819757 Sam Smith's acceptance speeches]. Popsugar.com. Retrieved 9 February 2015.</ref> In October 2017, Smith stated that their latest album, ''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'', showed \"the gay guy I've become\".<ref name=\"gender\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/sam-smith-i-feel-just-as-much-a-woman-as-i-am-man/news-story/1ffc1d95c5d053b246c89d80bd3887b5|title=Sam Smith: 'I feel just as much a woman as I am man'|date=24 October 2017|website=news.com.au|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Smith revealed a relationship with actor [[Brandon Flynn]] in an interview on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]''. In June 2018, it was announced that Smith and Flynn had split after nine months of dating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/06/28/sam-smith-brandon-flynn-split-entertainment-13-reasons-why/|title=Sam Smith and 13 Reasons Why star Brandon Flynn have split up after nine months|last=Glass|first=Jess|date=28 June 2018|website=[[PinkNews]]}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Smith came out as [[genderqueer]],<ref name=\"comes out as genderqueer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.towleroad.com/2017/10/sam-smith-genderqueer-feel-just-much-woman-man/|title=Sam Smith Comes Out as Genderqueer: 'I Feel Just as Much Woman as I am Man'|last=Towle|first=Andy|date=23 October 2017|publisher=Towleroad}}</ref> and said \"I feel just as much a woman as I am a man\",<ref name=\"gender\" /> talking about a period in their youth where they \"didn't own a piece of male clothing and would wear full makeup while attending school\".<ref name=\"NNN gq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/sam-smith-comes-out-as-gender-nonbinary/10/2017/|title=Sam Smith Comes Out As Gender-Nonbinary|last1=Voss|first1=Brandon|authorlink1=Brandon Voss|date=22 October 2017|website=www.newnownext.com|publisher=[[Logo TV]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608111805/http://www.newnownext.com/sam-smith-comes-out-as-gender-nonbinary/10/2017/|archivedate=8 June 2019|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://whatstrending.com/pop/24989-sam-smith-comes-out-as-gender-queer/|title=Sam Smith Comes Out As Gender Queer|last=Firer|first=Alex|date=23 October 2017|work=[[What's Trending]]}}</ref> In September 2019, Smith announced a decision to come out as [[Non-binary gender|non-binary]] and change their gender pronouns to [[Singular they|they/them]], stating, \"after a lifetime of being at war with my gender I've decided to embrace myself for who I am, inside and out...\"<ref name=\"pronouns\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-49688123 |title=Sam Smith changes pronouns to they/them |last=Hunte |first=Ben |date=2019-09-14|accessdate=14 September 2019|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"pronouns 2\">{{cite web |last1=Blackmom |first1=Michael |title=Sam Smith Announced That Their Gender Pronouns Are They/Them |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/michaelblackmon/sam-smith-announced-that-their-preferred-gender-pronouns |website=BuzzfeedNews |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nSmith is the third cousin of singer [[Lily Allen]] and actor [[Alfie Allen]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nme.com/news/lily-allen/74818 |title=Nick Grimshaw and BBC Sound of winner Sam Smith joke about Lily Allen's 'big mouth' |work=[[New Musical Express]] |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> Smith is the godparent of close friend and collaborator Jimmy Napes' son.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://instagram.com/p/0QED0yR2Tm/|title=Instagram|author=Smith, Sam|date=15 March 2015|access-date=15 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407172116/https://www.instagram.com/p/0QED0yR2Tm/|archive-date=7 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nSmith identifies as a [[feminist]].<ref name=\"feminist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/culture/arts/the-interview-sam-smith-on-why-hes-a-feminist/|title=The Interview: Grammy winner Sam Smith|last=Iannacci|first=Elio|date=16 January 2015|website=[[Maclean's]]|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> \n\nSmith has struggled with body image issues since their pre-teen years and has been open about this in interviews.<ref name=\"Wong\" />\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Sam Smith discography}}\n*''[[In the Lonely Hour]]'' (2014)\n*''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'' (2017)\n*[[Upcoming Sam Smith album]] (2020)<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B-XD8Vag2Kp/</ref>\n\n==Tours==\n*[[In the Lonely Hour Tour]] (2015)\n*[[The Thrill of It All Tour]] (2018)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Sam Smith}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sam Smith}}\n*{{Official website|http://samsmithworld.com|Official website (samsmithworld.com)}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180828040110/http://www.samsmithsinger.com/ Profile], samsmithsinger.com; accessed 14 February 2015.\n*[http://www.mtv.com/artists/sam-smith Smith profile], MTV.com; accessed 14 February 2015.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Adele]]<br />\"[[Skyfall (Adele song)|Skyfall]]\", 2012\n| after=[[Billie Eilish]]<br />\"[[No Time to Die (song)|No Time to Die]]\", 2020\n| title=''[[James Bond]]'' title artist\n|years=\"[[Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall]]\", 2015|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before = [[The National (band)|The National]]|title = ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' [[list of Saturday Night Live guests|musical guest]]|years = 29 March 2014|after = [[Pharrell Williams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]| before=[[Common (rapper)|Common]] and [[John Legend]]| after=[[Justin Hurwitz]] and [[Pasek and Paul|Benj Pasek and Justin Paul]]| years=2015}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]]|before=Common and John Legend|after=Justin Hurwitz and Benj Pasek and Justin Paul|years=2015}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Brit Award for Best New Artist]]| before=[[Bastille (band)|Bastille]]| after=[[Catfish and the Bottlemen]]|years=2015}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Grammy Award for Best New Artist]]| before=[[Macklemore & Ryan Lewis]]| after=[[Meghan Trainor]]| years=2015}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Brit Award for Rising Star]]| before=[[Tom Odell]]| after=[[James Bay (singer)|James Bay]]|years=2014}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Sam Smith}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Sam Smith|Awards for Sam Smith]]\n|list =\n{{Academy Award Best Original Song}}\n{{Brit Critics' Choice}}\n{{Brit British Breakthrough}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song}}\n{{Grammy Award for Record of the Year}}\n{{Grammy Award for Song of the Year}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best New Artist}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album}}\n{{BBC Sound of...}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Sam}}\n[[Category:Sam Smith (singer)| ]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:English tenors]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:English pop singers]]\n[[Category:English soul singers]]\n[[Category:English feminists]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Gay feminists]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:Genderqueer people]]\n[[Category:LGBT feminists]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from London]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Original Song Academy Award-winning songwriters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of British Youth Music Theatre]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for International Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Non-binary musicians]]\n", "text_old": "<!--The subject of this article about a living person uses the gender neutral pronoun 'they', so therefore the article does as well.-->\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{other people}}\n{{short description|English singer and songwriter}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Sam Smith\n| image            = Sam Smith Lollapalooza 2015-9 (cropped).jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Smith performing at the 2015 [[Lollapalooza]]\n| birth_name       = Samuel Frederick Smith\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|5|19}}\n| birth_place      = [[London]], England\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*songwriter}}\n| website          = {{URL|samsmithworld.com}}\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/sam-smith-mn0002509942|title=Sam Smith Biography & History|website=[[AllMusic]]|first=Andy|last=Kellman|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/01/arts/music/05sam-smith-new-album-the-thrill-of-it-all.html|title=The Tear-Stained Confessions of Sam Smith|website=[[The New York Times]]|first=Taffy|last=Brodesser-Akner|date=1 November 2017|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Soul music|soul]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/who-is-sam-smith-a-quick-primer-on-the-u-k-soul-singer-244251/|title=Who Is Sam Smith? A Quick Primer on the U.K. Soul Singer|website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|first=Nick|last=Murray|date=31 March 2014|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2014/05/29/sam-smith-gay-british-soul-singer/9711681/|title=U.K. soul singer Sam Smith comes out|website=[[USA Today]]|date=29 May 2014|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[pop-soul]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thetylt.com/entertainment/adele-sam-smith-uk-pop-soul|title=Favorite U.K. pop-soul singer: Adele or Sam Smith?|website=The Tylt|first=Deron|last=Dalton|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>}}\n| background       = solo_singer\n| years_active     = 2007\u2013present\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| label            = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]]\n*[[Jimmy Napes]]\n*[[Naughty Boy]]\n}}\n| module         = {{Infobox person\n  |child     = yes\n  |signature =\n }}\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Frederick Smith''' (born 19 May 1992) is an English singer and songwriter. They rose to prominence in October 2012 after being featured on [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure's]] breakthrough single \"[[Latch (song)|Latch]]\", which peaked at number eleven on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Smith was subsequently featured on [[Naughty Boy]]'s \"[[La La La (Naughty Boy song)|La La La]]\", which became a number one single in May 2013. In December 2013, they were nominated for the [[2014 Brit Awards|2014 Brit Critics' Choice Award]] and the [[BBC]]'s [[Sound of...|Sound of 2014]] poll,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25216850|title=Brits announce Critics' Choice 2014 shortlist|publisher=BBC|date=5 December 2013|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01ky6g6/profiles/samsmith|title=Sound of 2014 Profile: Sam Smith|publisher=BBC|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> winning both.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/brit-awards/10511427/Brits-Critics-Choice-Award-2014-Sam-Smith-announced-as-winner.html|title=Brits Critics' Choice Award 2014: Sam Smith announced as winner|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=12 December 2013|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25635440|title=BBC Sound of 2014: Sam Smith |publisher=BBC|date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\nSmith's debut studio album, ''[[In the Lonely Hour]]'', was released in May 2014 on [[Capitol Records UK]].<ref name=\"inthelonelyhour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2013/12/16/sam-smith-announces-debut-album-in-the-lonely-hour-shares-tour-dates/|title=Sam Smith announces debut album ''In the Lonely Hour'', shares tour dates|last=|first=|date=16 December 2013|website=|publisher=Fact|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"[[Lay Me Down (Sam Smith song)|Lay Me Down]]\", was released prior to \"La La La\". The album's second single, \"[[Money on My Mind]]\", became Smith's second number one single in the UK.<ref name=\"moneyonmymind\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/money-on-my-mind-ep/id775088328|title='Money on My Mind' \u2013 EP by Sam Smith|publisher=[[iTunes]] (UK)|accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref> The third single, \"[[Stay with Me (Sam Smith song)|Stay with Me]]\", was an international success, reaching number one in the UK and number two on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], while their singles \"[[I'm Not the Only One]]\" and \"[[Like I Can]]\" reached the top ten in the UK. The album won four awards, at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]], including [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]], [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]], [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], and nominations for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]]. \n\nFor their and [[Jimmy Napes]]' song \"[[Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall]]\", the theme for the [[James Bond in film|James Bond]] film ''[[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]]'' (2015), Smith won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Golden Globe Award]] and the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]. Their second studio album, ''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'', was released in November 2017 and debuted atop the UK and US album charts. The lead single, \"[[Too Good at Goodbyes]]\", reached number one in the UK and Australia and number four in the US. Smith released the single \"[[Promises (Calvin Harris and Sam Smith song)|Promises]]\" with [[Calvin Harris]], and it reached number one in the UK. Smith initially released \"[[Dancing with a Stranger]]\", with [[Normani]], as the lead single for Smith's [[Upcoming Sam Smith album|third studio album]], which reached the top ten in the UK and the US and was nominated for [[Brit Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] at the [[2020 Brit Awards]], along with \"[[How Do You Sleep? (Sam Smith song)|How Do You Sleep?]]\", a cover of [[Donna Summer|Donna Summer's]] 1977 classic \"[[I Feel Love (Sam Smith song)|I Feel Love]]\", and \"[[To Die For (Sam Smith song)|To Die For]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/sam-smith-announces-new-album-to-die-for/|title=Sam Smith Announces New Album To Die For, Shares New Song|last=Bloom|first=Madison|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> until the album was postponed due to the 2020 [[Coronavirus disease|Covid-19]] pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/sam-smith-explains-why-they-changed-to-die-for-album-title-and-its-release-date-amid-coronavirus|title=Sam Smith explains why they changed to die for album title|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The single \u201c[[I'm Ready (Sam Smith and Demi Lovato song)|I'm Ready]]\u201d with [[Demi Lovato]], was then released as the lead single for the upcoming album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9360112/sam-smith-demi-lovato-im-ready-video|title=Sam Smith & Demi Lovato&#39;s &#39;I&#39;m Ready&#39; Video: Watch|date=2020-04-16|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nSmith has won four [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]], three [[Brit Awards]], three [[Billboard Music Award|Billboard Music Awards]], and an [[American Music Awards|American Music Award]], as well as a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe]] and an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] through their career. Smith is [[genderqueer]] and uses [[singular they]] pronouns.<ref name=\"pronouns\" /><ref name=\"pronouns 2\" />\n\n==Early life==\nSamuel Frederick Smith<ref>{{cite web |url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/writer.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&querytype=WriterID&keyid=1481472&keyname=SMITH+SAMUEL+FREDERICK&CAE=686735199&Affiliation=PRS |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140131205650/http://repertoire.bmi.com/writer.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&querytype=WriterID&keyid=1481472&keyname=SMITH+SAMUEL+FREDERICK&CAE=686735199&Affiliation=PRS |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 January 2014 |title=Songwriter/Composer: Smith, Samuel Frederick |work=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] |accessdate=17 May 2014 }}</ref> was born on 19 May 1992<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web | url = http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sam-smith-mn0002509942/biography | title= Artist Biography |first= James | last= Wilkinson | publisher=AllMusic.com | accessdate= 28 May 2014}}</ref> in [[London]] to Frederick Smith and broker Kate Cassidy.<ref name=allmusic /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/4445012/Banker-claims-she-was-sacked-for-promoting-sons-pop-career.html|title=Banker claims she was sacked for promoting son's pop career|author=Daily Telegraph reporter|date=3 February 2009|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> Smith was bullied for [[gynecomastia]] as a child and had liposuction at age 12.<ref name=\"Wong\">{{cite news |last1=Wong |first1=Curtis M. |title=Sam Smith Opens Up About Gender Identity, Body Image In Candid Interview |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/sam-smith-gender-identity-interview_n_5c8bf783e4b0d7f6b0f34199 |accessdate=March 17, 2019 |work=HuffPost |date=March 15, 2019}}</ref> They were part of [[British Youth Music Theatre|Youth Music Theatre UK]] and appeared in the troupe's 2007 production of ''Oh! Carol'', a musical featuring the music of [[Neil Sedaka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youthmusictheatreuk.org/alumni|title=Alumni Youth Music Theatre UK|date=17 December 2013}}</ref> Before entering the musical theatre, Smith had been in jazz bands.<ref name=\"bestfit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thelineofbestfit.com/features/interviews/sam-smith-every-day-i-think-about-how-insane-this-is-145738|title=Sam Smith: \"Every day I think about how insane this is\"|work=The Line Of Best Fit|date=14 February 2014|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> While studying studied singing and songwriting under jazz pianist [[Joanna Eden]] for a number of years,<ref name=\"fader\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/05/28/sam-smith-cover-story-interview/|title= Sam Smith Opens up About Life and Love|work=[[The Fader]]|accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref> Smith attended [[St Mary's Catholic School (Bishop's Stortford)|St Mary's Catholic School]] in [[Bishop's Stortford]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/News/Bishops-Stortford/Former-Stortford-schoolboy-Sam-Smith-gears-up-for-tonights-Brit-Awards-20140219164127.htm|title=Former Stortford schoolboy Sam Smith gears up for tonight's Brit awards|date=19 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531131254/http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/News/Bishops-Stortford/Former-Stortford-schoolboy-Sam-Smith-gears-up-for-tonights-Brit-Awards-20140219164127.htm|archivedate=31 May 2014}}</ref> and was a member of the Bishop's Stortford Junior Operatics (now Bishops Stortford Musical Theatre Society) and the Cantate Youth Choir.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cantate.co.uk|title=Home \u2013 cantate.co.uk|publisher=Cantate.co.uk|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n===2008\u20132009: Career beginnings with debut singles===\nSmith released two singles before 2010, \"Bad Day All Week\" and \"When It's Alright\".\n\n===2012\u20132013: Breakthrough===\nSmith was featured on the [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]] song \"[[Latch (song)|Latch]]\", which was released on 8 October 2012 and peaked at No. 11 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. In February 2013, Smith released the first single from the debut album, \"[[Lay Me Down (Sam Smith song)|Lay Me Down]]\", and later in the year featured on [[Naughty Boy]]'s single \"[[La La La (Naughty Boy song)|La La La]]\". It was released on 19 May 2013 and peaked at No. 1 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Smith's first EP ''[[Nirvana (EP)|Nirvana]]'' was released the following year. The first song on the EP, titled \"[[Safe with Me]]\", is produced by Two Inch Punch and was first broadcast on [[MistaJam]]'s [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] show on 24 July 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crackintheroad.com/music/23303-new-sam-smith-safe-with-me/|title=New: Sam Smith \u2013 Safe With Me|publisher=Crack in the Road|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=24 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006123254/http://www.crackintheroad.com/music/23303-new-sam-smith-safe-with-me#|archive-date=6 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The second song on the EP is titled \"Nirvana\" and is produced by Craze & Hoax and Jonathan Creek. The EP also includes Smith's acoustic solo version of \"Latch\" and a live version of \"I've Told You Now\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/nirvana-ep/id708375165|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Nirvana \u2013 EP by Sam Smith|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> Smith released the Disclosure, [[Nile Rodgers]], and [[Jimmy Napes]] collaboration \"Together\" on 25 November 2013 as the only single from ''[[Settle: The Remixes]]''.\n\n===2014\u20132016: ''In the Lonely Hour'' and international success===\n[[File:Sam Smith 2 (15425586230).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Smith singing in Glasgow in 2014]]\nThe second single from Smith's debut album, titled \"[[Money on My Mind]]\", was released on 16 February 2014. It was announced on 16 December that Smith's debut studio album, titled ''[[In the Lonely Hour]]'', would be released on 26 May 2014 through [[Capitol Records]].<ref name=\"inthelonelyhour\"/> Smith described the album as \"all about unrequited love\" as a result of personal experience, having never been loved back by any of their love interests.<ref name=\"Sound of Boston\">{{cite web|url=http://soundofboston.com/angel-cambridge-sam-smith/|title=The Angel of Cambridge: Sam Smith|work=Sound of Boston|last=Ollman|first=Jonah|date=28 March 2014|accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref> The album reached number one in the [[UK Albums Chart]] and number two on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and by 5 November it had become the second biggest selling album of 2014 in the US behind only ''[[1989 (Taylor Swift album)|1989]]'' by [[Taylor Swift]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|title=Official: Taylor Swift's '1989' Debuts With 1.287 Million Sold In First Week|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6304536/official-taylor-swifts-1989-debuts-with-1287-million-sold-in|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=4 November 2014|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sam-smiths-debut-album-on-track-to-knock-coldplay-off-number-1-3042/|title=Sam Smith's debut album on track to knock Coldplay off Number 1|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref> In January 2015, ''In the Lonely Hour'' was named the second best selling album of 2014 in the UK, behind ''[[x (Ed Sheeran album)|x]]'' by [[Ed Sheeran]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30641372 \"UK album chart for 2014 dominated by British artists\"]. BBC. Retrieved 1 January 2014.</ref> A live version of album track \"I've Told You Now\", performed at [[St Pancras Old Church]], was made available as a free download as part of an [[Amazon.com]] promotion on 27 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Told-Live-Pancras-Church-London/dp/B00HG1ANVM|title=I've Told You Now (Live at St Pancras Old Church, London): Sam Smith|date=27 December 2013|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402175656/http://www.amazon.co.uk/Told-Live-Pancras-Church-London/dp/B00HG1ANVM#|archive-date=2 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album track \"Make It To Me\", co-written by Howard of Disclosure and Jimmy Napes, was made available as a free download as part of an [[iTunes Store]] promotion on 13 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/make-it-to-me-single/id785860884|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Make It To Me \u2013 Single by Sam Smith|publisher=[[iTunes]]|date=13 January 2014}}</ref> Smith went on their debut American headlining tour in the second quarter of 2014, with a setlist of primarily new material.<ref name=\"Sound of Boston\"/>\n\nOn 20 January 2014, Smith made their American television debut performing \"Latch\" with Disclosure on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]''. Smith also performed on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on 29 March 2014, performing the [[Gospel music|gospel]]-tinged \"[[Stay with Me (Sam Smith song)|Stay with Me]]\" and an acoustic version of \"Lay Me Down\".<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1724912/meet-sam-smith-british-bartender-set-take-saturday-night-live-stage.jhtml|title=Meet Sam Smith: The British Bartender Set To Take The 'Saturday Night Live' Stage - MTV.com|work=[[MTV]]|last=Montgomery|first=James|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"vh1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2014-03-28/sam-smith-saturday-night-live|title=Get To Know Sam Smith Before He Plays Saturday Night Live \u2013 Music News + Gossip \u2013 VH1 Music|work=[[VH1]]|last=Exton|first=Emily|date=28 March 2014|accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"queerty\">{{cite web|url=http://www.queerty.com/is-sam-smith-the-worlds-next-great-male-diva-20140327|title=Is Sam Smith The World's Next Great Male Diva? / Queerty|work=[[Queerty]]|last=Tharrett|first=Matthew|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=29 March 2014}}</ref> \"Stay with Me\" reached number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number two on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>[http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2014-05-31/ \"2014 Top 40 Official Singles Chart UK Archive (31 May 2014)\"]. Official Charts Company. Retrieved 5 December 2014.</ref><ref name=\"Billboard\">[http://www.billboard.com/artist/5811918/Sam+Smith/chart?f=379 \"Sam Smith Album & Single Chart History\"]. Billboard. Retrieved 5 December 2014.</ref> The fourth single from the album, \"[[I'm Not the Only One]]\", reached number three in the UK and number five in the US.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\nIn June 2014, Smith first appeared on the cover of ''[[The Fader]]'' in its 92nd issue.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefader.com/2014/05/28/sam-smith-cover-story-interview/ | title=Cover Story: Sam Smith Opens Up About Life and Love | publisher=The FADER | work=The FADER | date=28 May 2014| accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> In August 2014, their single \"Stay with Me\" was named Variance Magazine's Song of Summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://variancemagazine.com/sounds/3312-songs-of-summer-2014 |title=Readers Select 2014 Songs of Summer |publisher=Variancemagazine.com |date=12 August 2014 |accessdate=22 August 2014}}</ref> Smith performed \"Stay With Me\" live at the [[2014 MTV Video Music Awards]] on 24 August at [[The Forum (Inglewood)|The Forum]] in [[Inglewood, California]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sam Smith Is Performing at the 2014 VMAs And Tears Are Unavoidable|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1902436/sam-smith-vma-perfomer/?utm=share_twitter|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> On 15 November 2014, they joined the charity group [[Band Aid 30]] along with other British and Irish pop acts, recording the latest version of the track \"[[Do They Know It's Christmas?]]\" at [[Sarm West Studios]] in [[Notting Hill]], London, to raise money for the [[2014 Ebola outbreaks|2014 Ebola crisis]] in [[Western Africa]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Band Aid 30: One Direction among celebrity line-up|newspaper=Telegraph|date=11 November 2014 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11220735/Band-Aid-30-line-up-revealed.html |accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Sam_Smith_Lollapalooza_2015-3.jpg|thumb|right|upright|250px|Smith performing \"Stay With Me\" in Berlin, Germany in 2015]]\nIn 2015, it came to light that singer [[Tom Petty]], noting similarities between \"Stay with Me\" and his 1989 hit song \"[[I Won't Back Down]]\", had negotiated an out-of-court settlement with Smith in October 2014. Petty and co-composer [[Jeff Lynne]] were awarded 12.5 percent of the royalties from \"Stay with Me\", and the names of Petty and Lynne joined James John Napier (known professionally as [[Jimmy Napes]]) in the [[ASCAP]] song credit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/01/tom-petty-awarded-songwriting-royalties-for-sam-smiths-stay-with-me/|title=Update: Tom Petty awarded songwriting royalties for Sam Smith's \"Stay With Me\" \u2013 Consequence of Sound|work=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]], held on 8 February 2015, at the [[Staples Center]] in Los Angeles, Smith performed \"Stay with Me\" and also received four Grammy Awards: [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]], [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] (for \"Stay with Me\") and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]] (for ''In the Lonely Hour'').<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-31164562 \"Grammy Awards: Sam Smith wins four prizes\"]. BBC. Retrieved 26 February 2015.</ref> At the [[2015 Brit Awards]] held at [[The O2 Arena]] in London on 25 February, they performed \"Lay Me Down\", and won the Brit Awards for [[British Breakthrough Act]], and Global Success.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30839967 \"Brit Awards 2015: Winners list\"]. BBC. Retrieved 26 February 2015.</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, \"Lay Me Down\" was re-released as the sixth single from the album, peaking at number 8 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 (Smith's third US top 10 single).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6502503/mark-ronson-bruno-mars-hot-100-sam-smith-fetty-wap|work=Billboard|title=Mark Ronson, Bruno Mars Lead Hot 100; Sam Smith, Fetty Wap Hit Top 10|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=18 March 2015|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> The same month, Smith recorded another version of the song, featuring [[John Legend]], for the British charity telethon [[Comic Relief]], which reached number one in the UK.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/31902835 \"Sam Smith scores double number one in the UK charts\"]. BBC. Retrieved 20 March 2015</ref>  At the [[2015 Billboard Music Awards]] on 17 May, Smith received three Billboard Awards: Top Male Artist, Top New Artist, and Top Radio Songs Artist.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/6568580/billboard-music-awards-2015-winners-list|title=Billboard Music Awards 2015: See the Full Winners List|date=17 May 2015|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref> They featured on [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]]'s single \"[[Omen (Disclosure song)|Omen]]\", which was released on 27 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2015/07/disclosure-new-song-and-video-omen-f-sam-smith|title=Disclosure and Sam Smith Connect On \"Omen\"|date=27 July 2015|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2015, Smith and Jimmy Napes confirmed that they had composed \"[[Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall]]\", the theme song to ''[[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]]'', the 24th [[James Bond in film|James Bond]] film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34176304|title=Sam Smith records Bond's Spectre theme tune|author=BBC News reporter|date=8 September 2015|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref> The song was released on 25 September 2015 and became the first James Bond theme to reach number one in the UK.<ref name=\"Bond\"/> On 19 October, Smith was presented with two ''[[Guinness World Records]]''\u2014one for recording the first [[James Bond music|James Bond theme song]] to go to number one in the UK and another for scoring the most consecutive weeks in the UK top 10 by a debut album, for ''In the Lonely Hour''.<ref name=\"Bond\">{{cite news|title=Sam Smith's Stay With Me named song of the year|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34571560|agency=BBC|date=20 October 2015}}</ref> At the [[73rd Golden Globe Awards]] on 10 January 2016, they received the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Award for Best Original Song]] for \"Writing's on the Wall\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Golden Globes 2016: The Revenant wins top three awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35267777|publisher=BBC|date=11 January 2015}}</ref> On 14 January, the song earned Smith an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/oscar-nominations-complete-list-855398 |title=Oscar Nominations: The Complete List |work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=14 January 2016 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> In the nominations for the [[2016 Brit Awards]] announced on 14 January, the song was among the nominees for Best British Video.<ref>{{cite news|title= Brit Awards 2016: The nominations |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35319213 |work= BBC News Online |date= 14 January 2016 |accessdate= 22 January 2016}}</ref> Smith performed \"Writing's on the Wall\" at the Academy Awards on 28 February and, along with Napes, collected the prize for Best Original Song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sam-smith-wins-oscar-for-his-james-bond-spectre-theme-song-writings-on-the-wall__13954/|title=Sam Smith wins Oscar for his James Bond Spectre theme song|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=29 February 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref> In their acceptance speech, Smith referenced an article by [[Ian McKellen]] published before the awards ceremony that claimed no openly gay man had won an Oscar for Best Actor; Smith misquoted McKellen as saying that no gay man in general had won an Oscar. This was quickly discredited by openly gay recipient [[Dustin Lance Black]],<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.musictimes.com/articles/66393/20160229/sam-smith-mistakenly-thought-first-openly-gay-man-win-oscar.htm| title = Sam Smith Gaffes at Oscars with Misinformed Acceptance Speech, Shaky Performance| date = 29 February 2016| website = Music Times| accessdate = 1 March 2016}}</ref> but McKellen mentioned that the error \"doesn't detract\" from Smith's achievement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/01/arts/sam-smith-the-only-openly-gay-oscar-winner-not-really.html |title=Sam Smith, the Only Openly Gay Oscar Winner? Not Really |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Yonette |last=Joseph |date=29 February 2016 |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''The Thrill of It All''===\nThroughout 2016, Smith released footage of themself in the studio working on new music, leading up to the release of their second studio album. In late 2016, Smith was said to be working with [[Adam Lambert]] on new material. In early 2017, it was reported that Smith would be releasing their second album in September 2017 and had recorded with constant collaborator [[Jimmy Napes]] and [[Naughty Boy]]. In April 2017, Smith was said to have been in studio sessions with [[classical crossover]] group [[Clean Bandit]], working on a possible \"comeback single\". Along with Clean Bandit, record producer [[Timbaland]] and musician [[Frances (musician)|Frances]] said they had worked on songs for Smith's next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/music/clean-bandit-working-on-comeback-song-with-sam-smith/article_248112b6-c023-5ba5-8f78-8cd829bb6a39.html|title=Clean Bandit working on comeback song with Sam Smith?|publisher=NWI Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2017, Smith released a new single titled \"[[Too Good at Goodbyes]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://360musicng.org/sam-smith-good-goodbyes-official-single-cover/|title=Sam Smith \u2013 Too Good At Goodbyes (Official Single Cover)|work=360musicng.org|date=4 September 2017}}</ref> which debuted at number one in the United Kingdom and number five on the US Billboard Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Jack|title=Sam Smith scoops his sixth UK Number 1 single with Too Good at Goodbyes|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sam-smith-scoops-his-sixth-uk-number-1-single-with-too-good-at-goodbyes__20436/|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=15 September 2017|date=15 September 2017}}</ref> Their second studio album, ''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'', debuted atop the UK Albums Chart and the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], becoming their first number one album in the US.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8038264/sam-smith-billboard-artist-100-the-thrill-of-it-all|title=Sam Smith Hits No. 1 on Billboard Artist 100, Thanks to 'The Thrill of It All' Debut|work=Billboard|access-date=15 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sam-smith-s-the-thrill-of-it-all-debuts-at-number-1-on-the-official-albums-chart-this-is-a-dream-come-true-__20979|title=Sam Smith's The Thrill Of It All debuts at Number 1 on the Official Albums Chart: \"This is a dream come true\"|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|author=Rob Copsey|date=10 November 2017|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref> On 20 March 2018, Smith started The Thrill of It All Tour, which visited Europe, North America, Asia, New Zealand and Australia. On 27 March 2018, they released \"[[Pray (Sam Smith song)|Pray]]\" featuring American rapper [[Logic (musician)|Logic]]. On 17 August 2018, the singer collaborated as the main vocalist on [[Calvin Harris]]'s new track \"[[Promises (Calvin Harris and Sam Smith song)|Promises]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenocturnaltimes.com/calvin-harris-sam-smith-debut-promises/|title=Calvin Harris & Sam Smith Debut \"Promises\" {{!}} The Nocturnal Times|website=www.thenocturnaltimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2 December 2018}}</ref> The song became Smith's seventh number one hit on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and their first top song on ''Billboard'''s [[Dance/Mix Show Airplay]] chart.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8478334/calvin-harris-ties-rihanna-dance-mix-show-airplay-chart-toppers|title=Calvin Harris Ties Rihanna for Most Dance/Mix Show Airplay Chart No. 1s With 'Promises'|work=Billboard|access-date=2 December 2018}}</ref> They also released the song \"[[Fire on Fire]]\" as the ''[[Watership Down (miniseries)|Watership Down]]'' soundtrack.\n\n===2019\u20132020: Third album===\nIn January 2019, Smith released the song \"[[Dancing with a Stranger]]\" with [[Normani]] as a single and it reached the top ten in the UK, the US and other countries.\n\nOn 6 July 2019, [[New 102.7]] radio host Mike Adam announced the song \"[[How Do You Sleep? (Sam Smith song)|How Do You Sleep?]]\" on their Twitter account on 6 July.<ref name=\"Mike Adam\">{{cite tweet|user=MikeAdamOnAir|number=1147316780173529089|title=New music from @samsmith is on the way!!! Sam will drop \"HOW DO YOU SLEEP?\" on July 19th!!! The upcoming #SamSmith single was written with Savan, IIya and Max Martin... if that isn't a recipe for a great song, I don't know what is!|date=6 July 2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> On 9 July 2019, Smith posted on social media that an announcement would be made the following day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=samsmith|number=1148592325398007809|title=\ud83d\udd25\ud83e\udde1 sound on \ud83d\udc9b\ud83d\udd25|date=9 July 2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://portalpopline.com.br/sam-smith-prepara-anuncio-especial-para-esta-quarta-feira-10/|title=Sam Smith prepara an\u00fancio especial para esta quarta-feira (10)|website=Portalpopline|language=Portuguese|last=Medeiros|first=Kavad|date=9 July 2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> The pre-order link became active on 10 July,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://samsmith.world/HDYS|title=Sam Smith \u2013 How Do You Sleep?|website=samsmith.world|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref> and later the same day, they formally announced and shared a clip of the song.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=samsmith|number=1148921364377735169|title=HOW DO YOU SLEEP? July 19th|date=10 July 2019|accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, in a new interview with ''The Zach Sang Show'', Smith expressed excitement about their upcoming record, which will land sometime in 2020. The singer also confirmed that their newest offering will feature fewer ballads and plenty of poppier tracks in the vein of their recent two previous singles. \"I feel like I have recently shown a side of me which I normally keep to myself or for my family and friends,\" Smith told Sang. \"I showed everyone it and everyone loved it. It's almost given me permission to kinda do what I've always dreamed of doing but I was always scared to do, which is pop music.\" The singer also described having been spurred on to write new music following a 2018 collaboration with Calvin Harris, \"Promises\". \"I just naturally started getting back into the studio and started to write,\" they said. \"I caught this wind and started riding this wave and I haven't stopped writing since.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/sam-smith-confirms-new-album-coming-2020-2555740|title=Sam Smith confirms new pop-driven album is coming in 2020|date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February 2020, Smith revealed that a third studio album, then titled ''To Die For'', was scheduled to be released on 1 May 2020.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[MTV]]|author=Trey Alston|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 13, 2020|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3156531/sam-smith-to-die-for-album-announcement/|title=SAM SMITH TEASES NEW ALBUM WITH A (LITERALLY) GRABBY PHOTO}}</ref> Later on in the promotion, the album's release date was pushed back to June 2020.\n\nOn 30 March 2020, Smith announced that, due to the ongoing effects of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], they would be delaying the release of their [[Upcoming Sam Smith album|third album]] and would include a number of changes to the album track list and the title, as they would continue to work on it. However, they did state that it would still be released sometime within 2020.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B-XD8Vag2Kp/</ref>\n\n==Influences==\n{{multiple image\n| footer    = Smith cites [[Adele]] (left) and [[Amy Winehouse]] (right) as primary influences\n| image1    = ADELE LIVE 2016 - HELLO - ST.PAUL - night 1 - Copy.jpg\n| alt1      =Adele\n|width1  = 120\n| image2    = Amy Winehouse f4962007 crop.jpg\n| alt2      =Amy Winehouse\n|width2     = 120\n|align=right\n}}\nSmith cites [[Adele]] and [[Amy Winehouse]] as primary influences.<ref name=\"Capital FM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/sam-smith/news/adele-inspiration/|title=\"I Look Up To Her\" \u2013 Sam Smith On Being Inspired By Adele|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"4music\">\"This Week's Fresh Music\" (17 May 2014). [[4Music]]. Retrieved 28 July 2015</ref> In an interview with ''Rolling Stone'', they cited [[Whitney Houston]] and [[Mariah Carey]] as the greatest R&B voices.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Sam Smith Breaks Down 10 Great R&B Voices|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sam-smith-breaks-down-10-great-r-b-voices-20140513|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sam Smith: 5 Fact Facts About The 2015 Grammy Winner|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/sam-smith-5-fact-facts-about-2015-grammy-winner-1809396|website=International Business Times|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref> The singer also lists [[Chaka Khan]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]], and [[Lady Gaga]] as influences. Asked about the \"diva qualities\" of Smith's voice, the singer remarked:\n{{quote|\"It's all I listened to. I actually didn't listen to male vocalists until about two years ago. I just listened to Whitney Houston, [[Chaka Khan]]. Massive voices.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC Sound of 2014: Sam Smith|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-25635440|work=BBC News}}</ref>}}\n\nIn an October 2017 interview for ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'' magazine, Smith spoke of the impact of the success of Smith's close friend [[Ed Sheeran]]. \"It makes you push yourself. Watching him this past year has just been incredible, but yeah, of course it makes me hungry.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Sam Smith: Watching Ed Sheeran makes me push myself|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/music/news/sam-smith-watching-ed-sheeran-makes-me-push-myself-36130631.html|date=10 December 2017|website=Belfast Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn May 2014, Smith came out to the public as [[gay]], and acknowledged a relationship\u2014since ended\u2014with actor and model Jonathan Zeizel.<ref name=\"eonline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/546310/sam-smith-opens-up-about-being-gay-reveals-album-is-about-a-guy-who-didn-t-love-him-back|title=Sam Smith Opens Up About Being Gay, Reveals Album Is About a Guy Who Didn't Love Him Back|last=Malec|first=Brett|date=29 May 2014|publisher=E!|accessdate=28 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/30931139|title=Sam Smith confirms break-up on stage in Toronto|publisher=BBC|date=22 January 2015|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> At the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]] when \"Stay with Me\" won an award for Record of the Year, they said, \"I want to thank the man who this record is about, who I fell in love with last year. Thank you so much for breaking my heart because you got me four Grammys!\"<ref>[http://www.popsugar.com/entertainment/Sam-Smith-Grammys-Acceptance-Speeches-2015-36819757#photo-36819757 Sam Smith's acceptance speeches]. Popsugar.com. Retrieved 9 February 2015.</ref> In October 2017, Smith stated that their latest album, ''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'', showed \"the gay guy I've become\".<ref name=\"gender\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/sam-smith-i-feel-just-as-much-a-woman-as-i-am-man/news-story/1ffc1d95c5d053b246c89d80bd3887b5|title=Sam Smith: 'I feel just as much a woman as I am man'|date=24 October 2017|website=news.com.au|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Smith revealed a relationship with actor [[Brandon Flynn]] in an interview on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]''. In June 2018, it was announced that Smith and Flynn had split after nine months of dating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/06/28/sam-smith-brandon-flynn-split-entertainment-13-reasons-why/|title=Sam Smith and 13 Reasons Why star Brandon Flynn have split up after nine months|last=Glass|first=Jess|date=28 June 2018|website=[[PinkNews]]}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Smith came out as [[genderqueer]],<ref name=\"comes out as genderqueer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.towleroad.com/2017/10/sam-smith-genderqueer-feel-just-much-woman-man/|title=Sam Smith Comes Out as Genderqueer: 'I Feel Just as Much Woman as I am Man'|last=Towle|first=Andy|date=23 October 2017|publisher=Towleroad}}</ref> and said \"I feel just as much a woman as I am a man\",<ref name=\"gender\" /> talking about a period in their youth where they \"didn't own a piece of male clothing and would wear full makeup while attending school\".<ref name=\"NNN gq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/sam-smith-comes-out-as-gender-nonbinary/10/2017/|title=Sam Smith Comes Out As Gender-Nonbinary|last1=Voss|first1=Brandon|authorlink1=Brandon Voss|date=22 October 2017|website=www.newnownext.com|publisher=[[Logo TV]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608111805/http://www.newnownext.com/sam-smith-comes-out-as-gender-nonbinary/10/2017/|archivedate=8 June 2019|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://whatstrending.com/pop/24989-sam-smith-comes-out-as-gender-queer/|title=Sam Smith Comes Out As Gender Queer|last=Firer|first=Alex|date=23 October 2017|work=[[What's Trending]]}}</ref> In September 2019, Smith announced a decision to come out as [[Non-binary gender|non-binary]] and change their gender pronouns to [[Singular they|they/them]], stating, \"after a lifetime of being at war with my gender I've decided to embrace myself for who I am, inside and out...\"<ref name=\"pronouns\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-49688123 |title=Sam Smith changes pronouns to they/them |last=Hunte |first=Ben |date=2019-09-14|accessdate=14 September 2019|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"pronouns 2\">{{cite web |last1=Blackmom |first1=Michael |title=Sam Smith Announced That Their Gender Pronouns Are They/Them |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/michaelblackmon/sam-smith-announced-that-their-preferred-gender-pronouns |website=BuzzfeedNews |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nSmith is the third cousin of singer [[Lily Allen]] and actor [[Alfie Allen]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nme.com/news/lily-allen/74818 |title=Nick Grimshaw and BBC Sound of winner Sam Smith joke about Lily Allen's 'big mouth' |work=[[New Musical Express]] |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> Smith is the godparent of close friend and collaborator Jimmy Napes' son.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://instagram.com/p/0QED0yR2Tm/|title=Instagram|author=Smith, Sam|date=15 March 2015|access-date=15 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407172116/https://www.instagram.com/p/0QED0yR2Tm/|archive-date=7 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nSmith identifies as a [[feminist]].<ref name=\"feminist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/culture/arts/the-interview-sam-smith-on-why-hes-a-feminist/|title=The Interview: Grammy winner Sam Smith|last=Iannacci|first=Elio|date=16 January 2015|website=[[Maclean's]]|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> \n\nSmith has struggled with body image issues since their pre-teen years and has been open about this in interviews.<ref name=\"Wong\" />\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Sam Smith discography}}\n*''[[In the Lonely Hour]]'' (2014)\n*''[[The Thrill of It All (Sam Smith album)|The Thrill of It All]]'' (2017)\n*[[Upcoming Sam Smith album]] (2020)<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B-XD8Vag2Kp/</ref>\n\n==Tours==\n*[[In the Lonely Hour Tour]] (2015)\n*[[The Thrill of It All Tour]] (2018)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Sam Smith}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sam Smith}}\n*{{Official website|http://samsmithworld.com|Official website (samsmithworld.com)}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180828040110/http://www.samsmithsinger.com/ Profile], samsmithsinger.com; accessed 14 February 2015.\n*[http://www.mtv.com/artists/sam-smith Smith profile], MTV.com; accessed 14 February 2015.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Adele]]<br />\"[[Skyfall (Adele song)|Skyfall]]\", 2012\n| after=[[Billie Eilish]]<br />\"[[No Time to Die (song)|No Time to Die]]\", 2020\n| title=''[[James Bond]]'' title artist\n|years=\"[[Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall]]\", 2015|\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before = [[The National (band)|The National]]|title = ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' [[list of Saturday Night Live guests|musical guest]]|years = 29 March 2014|after = [[Pharrell Williams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]| before=[[Common (rapper)|Common]] and [[John Legend]]| after=[[Justin Hurwitz]] and [[Pasek and Paul|Benj Pasek and Justin Paul]]| years=2015}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]]|before=Common and John Legend|after=Justin Hurwitz and Benj Pasek and Justin Paul|years=2015}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Brit Award for Best New Artist]]| before=[[Bastille (band)|Bastille]]| after=[[Catfish and the Bottlemen]]|years=2015}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Grammy Award for Best New Artist]]| before=[[Macklemore & Ryan Lewis]]| after=[[Meghan Trainor]]| years=2015}}\n{{succession box| title=[[Brit Award for Rising Star]]| before=[[Tom Odell]]| after=[[James Bay (singer)|James Bay]]|years=2014}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Sam Smith}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Sam Smith|Awards for Sam Smith]]\n|list =\n{{Academy Award Best Original Song}}\n{{Brit Critics' Choice}}\n{{Brit British Breakthrough}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song}}\n{{Grammy Award for Record of the Year}}\n{{Grammy Award for Song of the Year}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best New Artist}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album}}\n{{BBC Sound of...}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Sam}}\n[[Category:Sam Smith (singer)| ]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:English tenors]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:English pop singers]]\n[[Category:English soul singers]]\n[[Category:English feminists]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Gay feminists]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:Genderqueer people]]\n[[Category:LGBT feminists]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from London]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Original Song Academy Award-winning songwriters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of British Youth Music Theatre]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for International Album of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Non-binary musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Wbrackett", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Smith"}
