stal]] [[Prairie]] (''20'').<ref name=\"Conservation Biology Institute\">{{cite web|url=https://databasin.org/datasets/1c7a301c8e6843f2b4fe63fdb3a9fe39|accessdate=August 5, 2019|title=U.S. Potential Natural Vegetation, Original Kuchler Types, v2.0 (Spatially Adjusted to Correct Geometric Distortions)}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Category see also|People from Beach Haven, New Jersey}}\nPeople who were born in, residents of, or otherwise closely associated with Beach Haven include:\n* [[Doc Cramer]] (1905\u20131990), [[center fielder]] who played for four [[American League]] teams<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballhistorian.com/html/american_heroes.cfm?page=114|title=1945 World Champion Detroit Tigers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928002021/http://www.baseballhistorian.com/html/american_heroes.cfm?page=114 |archive-date=2007-09-28|website=Baseball Historian|accessdate=July 29, 2007|quote=Doc Cramer...born in Beach Haven, New Jersey...}}</ref>\n* [[Elizabeth Warder Crozer Campbell]] (1893-1971), archaeologist\n* [[Lara Knutson]] (born 1974), artist and industrial designer, who was influenced by being fascinated as a child by the play of light on seashells along the beachfront in her hometown, as well as the texture they would create when crushed.<ref>[https://americanart.si.edu/artist/lara-knutson-30182 Lara Knutson | Smithsonian American Art Museum]. Accessed September 10, 2019. \"Born Beach Haven, New Jersey\"</ref>\n* [[Joe Piscopo]] (born 1951), comedian and actor<ref>{{cite news|last=Weaver|first=Donna|url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/news/breaking/piscopo-sells-out-fundraiser-for-sandy-storm-responders-in-stafford/article_98e94512-47f0-11e2-b535-001a4bcf887a.html|title=Piscopo sells out fundraiser for Sandy storm-responders in Stafford, Beach Haven|newspaper=[[The Press of Atlantic City]]|date=December 16, 2012|accessdate=August 25, 2013|quote=Comedian Joe Piscopo, who rode on a Beach Haven garbage truck long before he became famous, is returning to perform Friday at a sold-out fundraiser to help raise money for emergency responders who were affected by Hurricane Sandy. Kim England, of Stafford Township, said he grew spending his summers at his parents' Beach Haven home along with Piscopo, whose parents also own a home there}}</ref>\n* [[Henry Wisniewski]] (1908-1988), [[American football]] player and dentist.<ref>Dixon, Edith L. [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222611/http://articles.philly.com/1988-10-29/news/26273862_1_dentist-pennsylvania-dental-school-athlete \"Henry F. Wisniewski, 80, Dentist And Former Athlete\"], ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', October 29, 1988, backed up by the [[Internet Archive]] as of March 3, 2016. Accessed September 10, 2019.\"Dr. Henry F. Wisniewski, 80, a dentist and former star athlete at Camden High School and Fordham University, died yesterday at the Manahawkin Convalescent Center in Ocean County. He lived in Beach Haven Park.\"</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Beach Haven, New Jersey}}\n{{wikivoyage|Beach Haven}}\n* [http://www.beachhaven-nj.gov Beach Haven Borough]\n* [http://www.beachhavenschool.com Beach Haven Elementary School]\n* {{NJReportCard|29|0230|0|Beach Haven Elementary School}}\n* [https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_list.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=3401290 School Data for the Beach Haven Elementary School], [[National Center for Education Statistics]]\n* [http://www.srsd.net/ Southern Regional School District]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = Beaches of New Jersey\n | years  = \n | with   =\n | before = [[North Beach Haven, New Jersey|North Beach Haven]]\n | after  = [[Brigantine, New Jersey|Brigantine]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Ocean County, New Jersey}}\n\n[[Category:Beach Haven, New Jersey| ]]\n[[Category:1890 establishments in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in Ocean County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Faulkner Act (council\u2013manager)]]\n[[Category:Jersey Shore communities in Ocean County]]\n[[Category:Long Beach Island]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1890]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beach_Haven,_New_Jersey"}
{"title_page": "Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm\n| synonyms        = \n| image           = IPMN T2w ax-07 a.jpg\n| alt             = \n| caption         = Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm in magnetic resonance imaging.\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm''' ('''IPMN''') is a type of [[tumor]] that can occur within the cells of the [[pancreatic duct]]. IPMN tumors produce mucus,<ref name=\"JHUFAQ\">{{cite web |url=http://pathology.jhu.edu/pancreas/IPMN.php |title=Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasms of the Pancreas |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]]|accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> and this mucus can form [[pancreatic cyst]]s.<ref name=\"Campbell2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Campbell|first1=NM|last2=Katz|first2=SS|last3=Escalon|first3=JG|last4=Do|first4=RK|title=Imaging patterns of intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms of the pancreas: an illustrated discussion of the International Consensus Guidelines for the Management of IPMN|journal=Abdominal Imaging|date=March 2015|volume=40|issue=3|pages=663\u201377|doi=10.1007/s00261-014-0236-4|pmid=25219664}}</ref> Although intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms are [[benign tumor]]s, they can progress to [[pancreatic cancer]].<ref name=\"JHUFAQ\" /> As such IPMN is viewed as a [[precancerous condition]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Precancerous conditions of the pancreas - Canadian Cancer Society|url=http://www.cancer.ca/en/cancer-information/cancer-type/pancreatic/pancreatic-cancer/precancerous-conditions/?region=on|website=www.cancer.ca|accessdate=5 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> Once an intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm has been found, the management options include close monitoring and pre-emptive surgery.{{medical citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Diagnosis==\nBy [[histopathology]], IPMN is characterized on [[light microscopy]] by Mucinous epithelial cells,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pathologyoutlines.com/topic/pancreasipmn.html|title=Pancreas - Exocrine tumors / carcinomas - Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN)|website=Pathology Outlines|author=Diana Agostini-Vulaj}} Topic Completed: 1 July 2018. Revised: 9 March 2020</ref> and growth within the [[pancreatic duct]]s.<ref name=\"AdsayMino-Kenudson2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Adsay|first1=Volkan|last2=Mino-Kenudson|first2=Mari|last3=Furukawa|first3=Toru|last4=Basturk|first4=Olca|last5=Zamboni|first5=Giuseppe|last6=Marchegiani|first6=Giovanni|last7=Bassi|first7=Claudio|last8=Salvia|first8=Roberto|last9=Malleo|first9=Giuseppe|last10=Paiella|first10=Salvatore|last11=Wolfgang|first11=Christopher L.|last12=Matthaei|first12=Hanno|last13=Offerhaus|first13=G. Johan|last14=Adham|first14=Mustapha|last15=Bruno|first15=Marco J.|last16=Reid|first16=Michelle D.|last17=Krasinskas|first17=Alyssa|last18=Kl\u00f6ppel|first18=G\u00fcnter|last19=Ohike|first19=Nobuyuki|last20=Tajiri|first20=Takuma|last21=Jang|first21=Kee-Taek|last22=Roa|first22=Juan Carlos|last23=Allen|first23=Peter|last24=Castillo|first24=Carlos Fern\u00e1ndez-del|last25=Jang|first25=Jin-Young|last26=Klimstra|first26=David S.|last27=Hruban|first27=Ralph H.|title=Pathologic Evaluation and Reporting of Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasms of the Pancreas and Other Tumoral Intraepithelial Neoplasms of Pancreatobiliary Tract|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=263|issue=1|year=2016|pages=162\u2013177|issn=0003-4932|doi=10.1097/SLA.0000000000001173|pmc=4568174}}</ref> [[Mucin 5AC]] is a useful [[immunohistochemistry]] marker.<ref name=\"Pishvaian2017\">{{cite journal| author=Pishvaian MJ, Brody JR| title=Therapeutic Implications of Molecular Subtyping for Pancreatic Cancer. | journal=Oncology (Williston Park) | year= 2017 | volume= 31 | issue= 3 | pages= 159\u201366, 168 | pmid=28299752 | doi= | pmc= | url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/elink.fcgi?dbfrom=pubmed&tool=sumsearch.org/cite&retmode=ref&cmd=prlinks&id=28299752  }}</ref> !! Microscopy findings<ref name=\"Pishvaian2017\"/> !! Micrograph !! [[Immunohistochemistry]] markers<ref name=\"Pishvaian2017\"/> Characteristic genetic alterations are those of [[KRAS]] and [[GNAS complex locus|GNAS]].<ref name=\"Pishvaian2017\"/>\n\nFurther subtyping of IPMN can be done as either:<ref name=\"Salvia2010\">{{cite journal|last1=Salvia|first1=Roberto|title=Differences between main-duct and branch-duct intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms of the pancreas|journal=World Journal of Gastrointestinal Surgery|volume=2|issue=10|year=2010|pages=342|issn=1948-9366|doi=10.4240/wjgs.v2.i10.342|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n*[[Gross pathology]]: Main duct versus branch duct lesions, which determines surgical management\n*By [[light microscopy]] and [[immunohistochemistry]]:<ref name=\"IshidaEgawa2007\">{{cite journal|last1=Ishida|first1=Masaharu|last2=Egawa|first2=Shinichi|last3=Aoki|first3=Takeshi|last4=Sakata|first4=Naoaki|last5=Mikami|first5=Yukio|last6=Motoi|first6=Fuyuhiko|last7=Abe|first7=Tadayoshi|last8=Fukuyama|first8=Shoji|last9=Sunamura|first9=Makoto|last10=Unno|first10=Michiaki|last11=Moriya|first11=Takuya|last12=Horii|first12=Akira|last13=Furukawa|first13=Toru|title=Characteristic Clinicopathological Features of the Types of Intraductal Papillary-Mucinous Neoplasms of the Pancreas|journal=Pancreas|volume=35|issue=4|year=2007|pages=348\u2013352|issn=0885-3177|doi=10.1097/mpa.0b013e31806da090}}</ref> Gastric, intestinal, pancreaticbiliary, and oncocytic.\n\n[[File:Histopathology of intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm types.jpg|thumb|center|450px|Histopathology of IPMN types in a distal pancreatectomy specimen from a 60-year-old man, by gross pathology (center image), microscopy and [[immunohistochemistry]]: The resected specimen (c) revealed that the mural nodule in the MPD consisted of PB-type IPMN with high-grade dysplasia (adenocarcinoma) (a) with a diffuse positivity of p53 immunostaining (an insert) and KRAS mutation (G12V). The BD-IPMN of the body was lined by gastric mucinous epithelium showing low papillary configuration with mild epithelial stratification with the same KRAS mutation (d), and the proliferation of similar gastric IPMN components sequentially involved the bottom of the mural nodule and the wall of the surrounding dilated MPD (indicated by red arrowheads) (b). The BD-IPMN of the tail was lined by flat, monolayer gastric mucinous epithelium lacking cellular atypia and KRAS mutation (e).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shibata|first1=Hideki|last2=Ohike|first2=Nobuyuki|last3=Norose|first3=Tomoko|last4=Isobe|first4=Tomohide|last5=Suzuki|first5=Reika|last6=Imai|first6=Hideyuki|last7=Shiokawa|first7=Akira|last8=Takimoto|first8=Masafumi|last9=Tabuchi|first9=Akihiro|last10=Takano|first10=Yuichi|last11=Yamamura|first11=Eiichi|last12=Nagahama|first12=Masatsugu|last13=Takeyama|first13=Nobuyuki|last14=Yokomizo|first14=Kazuaki|last15=Mizukami|first15=Hiroki|last16=Tanaka|first16=Jun-ichi|last17=Aoki|first17=Takeshi|last18=Murakami|first18=Masahiko|title=A resected case of two branch duct-type intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms showing different clinical courses after a two-year follow-up|journal=Clinical Journal of Gastroenterology|volume=10|issue=3|year=2017|pages=274\u2013278|issn=1865-7257|doi=10.1007/s12328-017-0728-1|doi-access=free}}-<br>\"This article is distributed under the terms of the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/)\"</ref>]]\n\n==Treatment==\nThe treatment of choice for main-duct IPMNs is resection due to approximately 50% chance of malignancy. Side-branch IPMNs are occasionally monitored with regular CT or MRIs, but most are eventually resected, with a 30% rate of malignancy in these resected tumors. Survival 5 years after resection of an IPMN without malignancy is approximately 80%, 85% with malignancy but no lymph node spread and 0% with malignancy spreading to lymph nodes.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sohn|first=Taylor|title=Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasms of the Pancreas|journal=Annals of Surgery|date=June 2004|volume=239|issue=6|pages=788\u2013799|pmid=15166958|pmc=1356287|doi=10.1097/01.sla.0000128306.90650.aa}}</ref> Surgery can include the removal of the head of the pancreas (a [[pancreaticoduodenectomy]]), removal of the body and tail of the pancreas (a [[distal pancreatectomy]]), or rarely removal of the entire pancreas (a total pancreatectomy).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pathology.jhu.edu/pancreas/TreatmentSurgery.php|title= Pancreatic Surgery |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]] |accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> In selected cases the surgery can be performed using minimally invasive techniques such as [[laparoscopy]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pathology.jhu.edu/pancreas/TreatmentLaparoscopic.php|title=Laproscopic Pancreatic Surgery |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]] |accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> or robotic surgery. A study using Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Result Registry (SEER) data suggested that increased lymph node counts harvested during the surgery were associated with better survival in invasive IPMN patients.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wu|first=WM|title=An increased total resected lymph node count benefits survival following pancreas invasive intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms resection: an analysis using the surveillance, epidemiology, and end result registry database.|journal=PLOS ONE|date=Sep 2014|volume=9|issue=9|pages=e107962|pmid=25264746|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0107962|pmc=4179272}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1982, IPMN was reported as a \"mucin-producing tumor\" by Kazuhiko Ohashi of the Japanese Foundation for Cancer Research.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Pancreatic serous cystadenoma]]\n*[[Solid pseudopapillary neoplasm]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = \n|  ICD10           = {{ICD10|D13.6}}\n|  ICD9            = \n|  ICDO            = \n|  OMIM            = \n|  MedlinePlus     = \n|  MeSH            = \n|  GeneReviewsNBK  = \n|  GeneReviewsName = \n}}\n\n{{Digestive system neoplasia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasm}}\n[[Category:Gastrointestinal cancer]]\n[[Category:Pancreas disorders]]\n[[Category:Pancreatic cancer]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm\n| synonyms        = \n| image           = IPMN T2w ax-07 a.jpg\n| alt             = \n| caption         = Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm in magnetic resonance imaging.\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm''' ('''IPMN''') is a type of [[tumor]] that can occur within the cells of the [[pancreatic duct]]. IPMN tumors produce mucus,<ref name=\"JHUFAQ\">{{cite web |url=http://pathology.jhu.edu/pancreas/IPMN.php |title=Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasms of the Pancreas |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]]|accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> and this mucus can form [[pancreatic cyst]]s.<ref name=\"Campbell2015\">{{cite journal|last1=Campbell|first1=NM|last2=Katz|first2=SS|last3=Escalon|first3=JG|last4=Do|first4=RK|title=Imaging patterns of intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms of the pancreas: an illustrated discussion of the International Consensus Guidelines for the Management of IPMN|journal=Abdominal Imaging|date=March 2015|volume=40|issue=3|pages=663\u201377|doi=10.1007/s00261-014-0236-4|pmid=25219664}}</ref> Although intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms are [[benign tumor]]s, they can progress to [[pancreatic cancer]].<ref name=\"JHUFAQ\" /> As such IPMN is viewed as a [[precancerous condition]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Precancerous conditions of the pancreas - Canadian Cancer Society|url=http://www.cancer.ca/en/cancer-information/cancer-type/pancreatic/pancreatic-cancer/precancerous-conditions/?region=on|website=www.cancer.ca|accessdate=5 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> Once an intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm has been found, the management options include close monitoring and pre-emptive surgery.{{medical citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Diagnosis==\nBy [[histopathology]], IPMN is characterized on [[light microscopy]] by Mucinous epithelial cells,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pathologyoutlines.com/topic/pancreasipmn.html|title=Pancreas - Exocrine tumors / carcinomas - Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm (IPMN)|website=Pathology Outlines|author=Diana Agostini-Vulaj}} Topic Completed: 1 July 2018. Revised: 9 March 2020</ref> and growth within the [[pancreatic duct]]s.<ref name=\"AdsayMino-Kenudson2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Adsay|first1=Volkan|last2=Mino-Kenudson|first2=Mari|last3=Furukawa|first3=Toru|last4=Basturk|first4=Olca|last5=Zamboni|first5=Giuseppe|last6=Marchegiani|first6=Giovanni|last7=Bassi|first7=Claudio|last8=Salvia|first8=Roberto|last9=Malleo|first9=Giuseppe|last10=Paiella|first10=Salvatore|last11=Wolfgang|first11=Christopher L.|last12=Matthaei|first12=Hanno|last13=Offerhaus|first13=G. Johan|last14=Adham|first14=Mustapha|last15=Bruno|first15=Marco J.|last16=Reid|first16=Michelle D.|last17=Krasinskas|first17=Alyssa|last18=Kl\u00f6ppel|first18=G\u00fcnter|last19=Ohike|first19=Nobuyuki|last20=Tajiri|first20=Takuma|last21=Jang|first21=Kee-Taek|last22=Roa|first22=Juan Carlos|last23=Allen|first23=Peter|last24=Castillo|first24=Carlos Fern\u00e1ndez-del|last25=Jang|first25=Jin-Young|last26=Klimstra|first26=David S.|last27=Hruban|first27=Ralph H.|title=Pathologic Evaluation and Reporting of Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasms of the Pancreas and Other Tumoral Intraepithelial Neoplasms of Pancreatobiliary Tract|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=263|issue=1|year=2016|pages=162\u2013177|issn=0003-4932|doi=10.1097/SLA.0000000000001173|pmc=4568174}}</ref> [[Mucin 5AC]] is a useful [[immunohistochemistry]] marker.<ref name=\"Pishvaian2017\">{{cite journal| author=Pishvaian MJ, Brody JR| title=Therapeutic Implications of Molecular Subtyping for Pancreatic Cancer. | journal=Oncology (Williston Park) | year= 2017 | volume= 31 | issue= 3 | pages= 159-66, 168 | pmid=28299752 | doi= | pmc= | url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/elink.fcgi?dbfrom=pubmed&tool=sumsearch.org/cite&retmode=ref&cmd=prlinks&id=28299752  }} </ref> !! Microscopy findings<ref name=\"Pishvaian2017\"/> !! Micrograph !! [[Immunohistochemistry]] markers<ref name=\"Pishvaian2017\"/> Characteristic genetic alterations are those of [[KRAS]] and [[GNAS complex locus|GNAS]].<ref name=\"Pishvaian2017\"/>\n\nFurther subtyping of IPMN can be done as either:<ref name=\"Salvia2010\">{{cite journal|last1=Salvia|first1=Roberto|title=Differences between main-duct and branch-duct intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms of the pancreas|journal=World Journal of Gastrointestinal Surgery|volume=2|issue=10|year=2010|pages=342|issn=1948-9366|doi=10.4240/wjgs.v2.i10.342|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n*[[Gross pathology]]: Main duct versus branch duct lesions, which determines surgical management\n*By [[light microscopy]] and [[immunohistochemistry]]:<ref name=\"IshidaEgawa2007\">{{cite journal|last1=Ishida|first1=Masaharu|last2=Egawa|first2=Shinichi|last3=Aoki|first3=Takeshi|last4=Sakata|first4=Naoaki|last5=Mikami|first5=Yukio|last6=Motoi|first6=Fuyuhiko|last7=Abe|first7=Tadayoshi|last8=Fukuyama|first8=Shoji|last9=Sunamura|first9=Makoto|last10=Unno|first10=Michiaki|last11=Moriya|first11=Takuya|last12=Horii|first12=Akira|last13=Furukawa|first13=Toru|title=Characteristic Clinicopathological Features of the Types of Intraductal Papillary-Mucinous Neoplasms of the Pancreas|journal=Pancreas|volume=35|issue=4|year=2007|pages=348\u2013352|issn=0885-3177|doi=10.1097/mpa.0b013e31806da090}}</ref> Gastric, intestinal, pancreaticbiliary, and oncocytic.\n\n[[File:Histopathology of intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm types.jpg|thumb|center|450px|Histopathology of IPMN types in a distal pancreatectomy specimen from a 60-year-old man, by gross pathology (center image), microscopy and [[immunohistochemistry]]: The resected specimen (c) revealed that the mural nodule in the MPD consisted of PB-type IPMN with high-grade dysplasia (adenocarcinoma) (a) with a diffuse positivity of p53 immunostaining (a insert) and KRAS mutation (G12V). The BD-IPMN of the body was lined by gastric mucinous epithelium showing low papillary configuration with mild epithelial stratification with the same KRAS mutation (d), and the proliferation of similar gastric IPMN components sequentially involved the bottom of the mural nodule and the wall of the surrounding dilated MPD (indicated by red arrowheads) (b). The BD-IPMN of the tail was lined by flat, monolayer gastric mucinous epithelium lacking cellular atypia and KRAS mutation (e).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shibata|first1=Hideki|last2=Ohike|first2=Nobuyuki|last3=Norose|first3=Tomoko|last4=Isobe|first4=Tomohide|last5=Suzuki|first5=Reika|last6=Imai|first6=Hideyuki|last7=Shiokawa|first7=Akira|last8=Takimoto|first8=Masafumi|last9=Tabuchi|first9=Akihiro|last10=Takano|first10=Yuichi|last11=Yamamura|first11=Eiichi|last12=Nagahama|first12=Masatsugu|last13=Takeyama|first13=Nobuyuki|last14=Yokomizo|first14=Kazuaki|last15=Mizukami|first15=Hiroki|last16=Tanaka|first16=Jun-ichi|last17=Aoki|first17=Takeshi|last18=Murakami|first18=Masahiko|title=A resected case of two branch duct-type intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms showing different clinical courses after a two-year follow-up|journal=Clinical Journal of Gastroenterology|volume=10|issue=3|year=2017|pages=274\u2013278|issn=1865-7257|doi=10.1007/s12328-017-0728-1|doi-access=free}}-<br>\"This article is distributed under the terms of the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/)\"</ref>]]\n\n==Treatment==\nThe treatment of choice for main-duct IPMNs is resection due to approximately 50% chance of malignancy. Side-branch IPMNs are occasionally monitored with regular CT or MRIs, but most are eventually resected, with a 30% rate of malignancy in these resected tumors. Survival 5 years after resection of an IPMN without malignancy is approximately 80%, 85% with malignancy but no lymph node spread and 0% with malignancy spreading to lymph nodes.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sohn|first=Taylor|title=Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasms of the Pancreas|journal=Annals of Surgery|date=June 2004|volume=239|issue=6|pages=788\u2013799|pmid=15166958|pmc=1356287|doi=10.1097/01.sla.0000128306.90650.aa}}</ref> Surgery can include the removal of the head of the pancreas (a [[pancreaticoduodenectomy]]), removal of the body and tail of the pancreas (a [[distal pancreatectomy]]), or rarely removal of the entire pancreas (a total pancreatectomy).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pathology.jhu.edu/pancreas/TreatmentSurgery.php|title= Pancreatic Surgery |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]] |accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> In selected cases the surgery can be performed using minimally invasive techniques such as [[laparoscopy]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pathology.jhu.edu/pancreas/TreatmentLaparoscopic.php|title=Laproscopic Pancreatic Surgery |publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University]] |accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> or robotic surgery. A study using Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Result Registry (SEER) data suggested that increased lymph node counts harvested during the surgery were associated with better survival in invasive IPMN patients.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wu|first=WM|title=An increased total resected lymph node count benefits survival following pancreas invasive intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms resection: an analysis using the surveillance, epidemiology, and end result registry database.|journal=PLOS ONE|date=Sep 2014|volume=9|issue=9|pages=e107962|pmid=25264746|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0107962|pmc=4179272}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1982, IPMN was reported as a \"mucin-producing tumor\" by Kazuhiko Ohashi of the Japanese Foundation for Cancer Research.\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Pancreatic serous cystadenoma]]\n*[[Solid pseudopapillary neoplasm]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = \n|  ICD10           = {{ICD10|D13.6}}\n|  ICD9            = \n|  ICDO            = \n|  OMIM            = \n|  MedlinePlus     = \n|  MeSH            = \n|  GeneReviewsNBK  = \n|  GeneReviewsName = \n}}\n\n\n{{Digestive system neoplasia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasm}}\n[[Category:Gastrointestinal cancer]]\n[[Category:Pancreas disorders]]\n[[Category:Pancreatic cancer]]\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: a insert \u2192 an insert", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intraductal_papillary_mucinous_neoplasm"}
